.\" Automatically generated by Pandoc 1.18
.\"
.TH "aggregate" "1" "" "SequoiaDB User Manuals" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
aggregate \- retrieve the documents from the collection in the SequoiaDB
and return a cursor.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]\f[I]db.collectionspace.collection.aggregate(<subOp>...)\f[]\f[]
.SH CATEGORY
.PP
Collection
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The functions of aggregate() and find() are pretty similar to each
other.
It also retrieves the documents from the collection in the SequoiaDB and
return a cursor.
.SH PARAMETERS
.SS subOp ( \f[I]object\f[] )
.PP
\f[B]\f[I]Optional\f[]\f[].
Sub\-operation, 1 to N sub\-operations can be filled in the aggregate()
method.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
aggregate() method has only one parameter subOp, which represents 1~N
sub\-operations,each sub\-operation is a json object, separated by
commas sub\-operation.
Aggregation framework supports the following Sub\-operation parameters:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]$project\f[]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Select the output fields by specifying field names, 1 stands for output,
0 means do not output.
The rename of fields can be realized.
.RS 2
.PP
Format: \f[C]{$project:{field1:1,field:0,aliase:"$field3"}}\f[]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]$match\f[] Select records which match the criteria from the
collection, equivalent to the "WHERE" command in SQL.
.RS 2
.PP
Format: \f[C]{$match:{field:{$lte:value}}}\f[]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]$limit\f[]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Limit the number of returned records.
.RS 2
.PP
Format: \f[C]{$limit:10}\f[]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]$skip\f[]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Control the starting point of the result set, in other words, skip
specified number of records in the result set.
.RS 2
.PP
Format: \f[C]{$skip:5}\f[]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]$group\f[]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Divide the records into groups, similar to the "group by" command in
SQL, specify the grouping field by "_id".
.RS 2
.PP
Format: \f[C]{$group:{_id:"$field"}}\f[]
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[C]$sort\f[]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Sort the result set.
1 for ascending while 0 for descending.
.RS 2
.PP
Format: \f[C]{$sort:{field1:1,field2:\-1,...}}\f[]
.RE
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[]
.IP \[bu] 2
Description: aggregate() can have any number of sub\-operations, but
please be careful about the syntax of the parameters.
.SH RETURN VALUE
.PP
On success, aggregate() return the value of calculation.
.PP
On error, exception will be thrown.
.SH ERRORS
.PP
\f[C]aggregate()\f[] usually return the follow exception:
.IP \[bu] 2
SDB_OOM (\-2): Unable to allocate memory for creating collection.
.IP \[bu] 2
SDB_NOSPC (\-11): Out of space.
.IP \[bu] 2
SDB_DMS_EXIST (\-22): Collection already exist.
.IP \[bu] 2
SDB_DMS_CS_NOTEXIST (\-34): Collection space does not exist.
.PP
When error happen, use getLastErrMsg() to get the error message or use
getLastError() to get the error code.
See troubleshooting for more detail.
.SH HISTORY
.PP
Since v1.0
.SH Examples
.PP
Assume a collection stores records in following format:
.RS
.PP
{ no:1000,
.PD 0
.P
.PD
score:80,
.PD 0
.P
.PD
interest:["basketball","football"],
.PD 0
.P
.PD
major:"Computer Science and Technology",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
dep:"Computer Academy",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
info:{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
name:"Tom",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
age:25,
.PD 0
.P
.PD
gender:"male"
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.RE
.IP "1." 3
Select records according to the criteria, and specify the returned field
name.
.RS
.PP
> db.collectionspace.collection.aggregate(
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{$match:{$and:[{no:{$gt:1002}},{no:{$lt:1015}},{dep:"Computer
Academy"}]}},
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{$project:{no:1,"info.name":1,major:1}})
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"no": 1003,
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"info.name": "Sam",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"major": "Computer Software and Theory"
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"no": 1004,
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"info.name": "Coll",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"major": "Computer Engineering"
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"no": 1005,
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"info.name": "Jim",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"major": "Computer Engineering"
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
This aggregate operation firstly uses $match to select the records
.PD 0
.P
.PD
match the criteria, then uses $project to specify the names of the
.PD 0
.P
.PD
returned fields.
.RE
.IP "2." 3
Select records by criteria and divide the selected records into groups.
.RS
.PP
> db.collectionspace.collection.aggregate(
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{$match:{dep:"Computer Academy"}}, {$group:{_id:"$major",Major:{$first:"$major"}, avg_age:{$avg:"$info.age"}}})
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"Major": "Computer Engineering",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"avg_age": 25
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"Major": "Computer Science and Technology",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"avg_age": 22.5
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
{
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"Major": "Computer Software and Theory",
.PD 0
.P
.PD
"avg_age": 26
.PD 0
.P
.PD
}
.PD 0
.P
.PD
This operation firstly uses $match to select records that match the
.PD 0
.P
.PD
selecting criteria, then uses $group to divide the selected records by
.PD 0
.P
.PD
field "major", and uses $avg to return the average of the "age" field
.PD 0
.P
.PD
in each group.
.RE
.IP "3." 3
Select records by criteria, then group and sort the selected records,
limit the starting point of the result set and the number of returned
records.
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
\ \ >\ db.collectionspace.collection.aggregate(\ \ 
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ {$match:{interest:{$exists:1}}},\ \ 
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ {$group:{_id:"$major",avg_age:{$avg:"$info.age"},\ major:{$first:"$major"}}},\ \ 
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ {$sort:{avg_age:\-1,major:\-1}},\ \ 
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ {$skip:2},\ \ 
\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ {$limit:3})\ \ 
\ \ {\ \ 
\ \ \ \ "avg_age":\ 25,\ \ 
\ \ \ \ "major":\ "Computer\ Science\ and\ Technology"\ \ 
\ \ }\ \ 
\ \ {\ \ 
\ \ \ \ "avg_age":\ 22,\ \ 
\ \ \ \ "major":\ "Computer\ Software\ and\ Theory"\ \ 
\ \ }\ \ 
\ \ {\ \ 
\ \ \ \ "avg_age":\ 22,\ \ 
\ \ \ \ "major":\ "Physics"\ \ 
\ \ }\ 
\f[]
.fi
.PP
This aggregate operation firstly uses $match to select records match
.PD 0
.P
.PD
the criteria, then uses $group to group the records by "major", uses
.PD 0
.P
.PD
$avg to return the average of "age" field in each group, and sort the
.PD 0
.P
.PD
records in descending order, uses $skip to specify the starting point
.PD 0
.P
.PD
of the returned result, and $limit to limit the number of returned
.PD 0
.P
.PD
records.
